From Lab 7, I decided that my optimal set of cuts consisted of 4 cuts, two cuts on the mass feature and two on the d2 feature:

My optimal set of mass cuts: (left, right) = (124.98224260383364, 128.09318340257153)

My optimal set of d2 cuts: (left, right) = (0.27837101274447207, 1.0504993443653543)

After the 4 cuts, 24% of my signals was left, but only 2 out of 100000 background points were left. So I'm not sure if my choices on the cuts were correct. Also, with only two background data points left, I'm not sure if my significance calculations would be accurate.

In [5]:
mass_cuts = (124.98224260383364, 128.09318340257153)
d2_cuts = (0.27837101274447207, 1.0504993443653543)
def make_cuts(dataset):
    return (dataset["mass"] >= mass_cuts[0]) & (dataset["mass"] <= mass_cuts[1]) \
        & (dataset["d2"] >= d2_cuts[0]) & (dataset["d2"] <= d2_cuts[1])
bkgd_cuts = make_cuts(qcd)
signal_cuts = make_cuts(higgs)
data_high_cuts = make_cuts(data_high)
data_low_cuts = make_cuts(data_low)

# function to plot histograms
def compare(ax, data, signal, bkgd, param, n_higgs, n_qcd, sigmas = 4, num_bins = 200,fontsize = 20):
    left1 = np.min([np.min(bkgd),np.min(signal)])
    left2 = np.min([np.mean(bkgd)-sigmas*np.std(bkgd), np.mean(signal)-sigmas*np.std(signal)])
    left = np.max([left1,left2])
    right1 = np.max([np.max(bkgd),np.max(signal)])
    right2 = np.max([np.mean(bkgd)+sigmas*np.std(bkgd), np.mean(signal)+sigmas*np.std(signal)])
    bins = np.linspace(np.max([left1,left2]),np.min([right1,right2]),num_bins)
    weights_signal = [n_higgs/len(higgs)]*len(signal)
    weights_bkgd = [n_qcd/len(higgs)]*len(bkgd)
    ax.hist(data, bins=bins, alpha = 0.5, color = 'g',label = 'Observed data')
    ax.hist([signal,bkgd], bins=bins, alpha = 0.5, color= ['r','b'], stacked = True, label = ['Expected signal','Expected background'],\
             ls='dashed', weights = [weights_signal,weights_bkgd])
    ax.legend(prop={'size': fontsize})
    ax.set_ylabel("Counts",fontsize=fontsize)
    ax.set_xlabel(param,fontsize=fontsize)
    ax.set_title('%s: Histograms of observed data & expected background stacked on signal' % param,fontsize=int(fontsize*1.25))

3. 95% Confidence Level of signal yields

  • In the low luminosity data, the observed significance is less than 5- . We will calculate the 95% confidence level upper limit of signal yield.

I'm not sure the question is talking about the significance before or after event selections.

With my optimal cuts applied, the observed significance value I got was much larger than 5-sigmas. I'm not sure if anything went wrong.

  • Evaluate the expected 95% confidence level upper limit
  • Evaluate the observed 95% confidence level upper limit
  • Compare expectation to observation. Comment on your finding.

Assume that my expected/observed number of yields is x and my corresponding 95% confidence level upper limit is y, then we have

95% = \<probability that background is within (x-y, x)> / \<probability that background is within (0, x)>

\ - \<CDF of background at (x-y)> = 0.95*\

y = x - \<PPF of background at 0.05*\>

If we assume the real signal is from a uniform distribution, then the expected/observed 95% confidence level upper limit should be the observed/expected yields minus the (1-95%*(integral of background distribution from 0 to the observed/expected yields)) percentile of the background distribution.

I will calculate the confidence level upper limit assuming the backgrounds follow Poisson distributions.

In [12]:
def find_upper_limit(n_data,n_bkgd):
    return n_data - stats.poisson.ppf((1-0.95)*stats.poisson.cdf(n_data,n_bkgd),n_bkgd)
upper_limit = find_upper_limit(len(data_low), n_qcd_low)
upper_limit_cut_expected = find_upper_limit(n_cut_higgs_low + n_cut_qcd_low, n_cut_qcd_low)
upper_limit_cut_observed = find_upper_limit(n_cut_data_low,n_cut_qcd_low)
print("95 percent confidence level upper limit without event selection: %f" % upper_limit)
print("Expected 95 percent confidence level upper limit with my optimal cuts: %f" % upper_limit_cut_expected)
print("Observed 95 percent confidence level upper limit with my optimal cuts: %f" % upper_limit_cut_observed)

95 percent confidence level upper limit without event selection: 48.000000
Expected 95 percent confidence level upper limit with my optimal cuts: 2.657606
Observed 95 percent confidence level upper limit with my optimal cuts: 5.000000

With my optimal cuts applied, my expected and observed upper limits are almost exactly the same as the expected and observed yields. This is because my expected value of background counts (which is 0.0086) is too small to influence my signal observations.
